title: For Sale/Trade:  Collectors grade 1905
postcontent: Collectors grade exapmle from my personal collection. The nicest example of the early “bright blade” Model 1905 bayonet having its original factory edge never ground down. It was made up to the start of WW1 when they began to darken the blades, and later most of the bright blade models were refinished, leaving the survivors scarce and desirable. This one was made at RIA armory in 1909. Walnut grip scales retain their rough turning texture and have only the GI oil finish. Hilt and crossguard retain about 90% of the original blued finish, Pommel and the top and bottom edges of the hilt retain most the their blue finish. The scabbard is a VG Model 1905 leather covered scabbard which originally had a Krag style swivel hook. These were converted after adoption of the M1910 belt system by removal of the swivel hook and addition of a leather collar with a M1910 hook. There are two types of conversion and this is the “type 3” discussed in Gary Cunningham’s “American Military Bayonets of the 20th Century” on pages 29-30. scabbard tip stitching has split very slightly at the end although it is somewhat scuffed. A far above average example of the early M1905 bayonet and the altered 1905/1910 scabbard !!Reply by email call or text 7205175213Trade for any quality firearms in the general ballpark value.

title: For Trade:  Yugoslavian M70A Milled Underfolder
location: Fridley / Burnsville, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent: Gunsmith built from a parts kit utilizing the original receiver portions with the necessary evil FA features removed per ATF requirement.  These are what the collecting community calls a "Re-Weld".  Hate that word, but it is what it is.    Picked this up in the recent trade and its extremely well built, but just not my cup of tea.  Its more for a collector that will appreciate that the M70A is the earliest of the Zastava underfolders and the early features are highly desirable.  From an examination, the only parts that are not correct for a M70A milled rifle is the Dust Cover, Gas Tube, and pistol grip.  Those are later parts from the M70AB.Overall in Good condition with a good bore that has a hint of frost from the corrosive M67 ammo that was in use in Croatia at the time.  Absent a trade, I am open to reasonable offers on this rifle.  Keep in mind this is a collectible variant and not some CAI Late feature Gravel Pit blaster.  M70A PARTS KITS can sell for upwards of $800 to 1000 at auction.

title: For Sale:  Historic original Long Tom 16 gauge shotgun - 36" barrel
postcontent: "Long Toms" were single-shot shotguns available in both 12- or 16-gauge and sported extra-long 36- or 40-inch barrels. A true Long Tom has only the two words "Long Tom" stamped on the side and carries no other brand, make or model numbers.  They were made by the Crescent Tool Company (the same company responsible for the legendary "Crescent Wrench,") and were manufactured between 1908 and 1916 to be sold in hardware stores and the Sears and Roebuck catalog.  Some sources claim they were also manufactured under contract by other companies, such as Harrington and Richardson.  The extra-long barrel made squirrel and bird hunting possible out to 50 yards or more.  I've also shot slugs out of this gun and I'm sure it would make a viable deer gun.  This particular example was bought new by my grandfather from the Sears catalog and used mainly for squirrel hunting during most of the first half of the last century.  I still remember the taste of pan-fried squirrel taken with this shotgun, and this was the first gun I ever shot, the first gun I ever hunted with, the first gun I ever shot a squirrel with, and the first gun I ever owned.  I feel like I've gotten a lifetime's worth of use out of this gun, but now I live overseas every other two years and it doesn't fit in my gun safe and I don't get to hunt anymore and I'd rather see someone get some use and enjoyment out of it instead of just having it sit in storage for the next 15 years.  It's got quite the patina of surface rust, having never had any work done to it, and it sports some electrical tape wrapped around the wrist of the stock, probably covering a crack, along with a hand-whittled plastic butt pad that my grandfather added, I guess for a better length of pull.  However the bore is in remarkably good condition, with a surprisingly small amount of pitting, and it's still a fun gun to shoot, especially with the spring loaded ejector that shoots the empty shell out with zeal when the action is broken open.  It shoulders and points very comfortably despite the length, and it's actually in better condition than one I saw on gunbroker.  In a perfect world I'd take a few weeks to polish it up and reblue all the metal, sand and refinish the stock, and replace the plastic buttpad with a rubber one.  But I can't justify spending the time and money knowing that I won't get a chance to shoot it and won't even be able to hang it on my wall where I'll be living.  Let my loss be your gain; I can even throw in a box or two of shells.  Close up pics available upon request.CASH ONLY - NO TRADES

postcontent:
This is a unique opportunity to own the gun, holster, and belt used by a police officer in New Jersey. This police package comes to us from an estate sale.
The revolver is a Smith & Wesson Model blued 10-5 that shows "character" and wears it with pride! This was the everyday carry weapon for this police officer until his retirement many years ago. Bore and cylinder are clean and everything feels tight. The rear sights and front ramp have white paint lightly dabbed on for the "old school" edition of fiber optic sights we have today.
The revolver has lots of holster wear and some light freckling in a few spots, but I think it is in better aesthetic condition than I would have expected from a career long everyday use and carry gun. The grips closely resemble custom-made dark walnut Bull's-eye target thumb rest grips. There is some wear in a couple of areas, primarily on the inside corners where they rubbed while in the holster.
My experience with Model 10-5 revolvers is that they are really fine shooters with nice triggers. I took this one out to the gun range tonight thinking I would shoot the handful of loose .38 caliber I had in a range bag just to make sure it fired okay. That was just a tease, as I ended up shooting that handful and a box of 50 Remington factory ammunition. It is a really good shooting gun with a nice trigger and the custom grips made for a really comfortable hold and lack of felt recoil.
The holster is a Jay-Pee Spring Lock Safety Swivel Holster that features a trigger guard click retention button to keep the pistol securely inside the holster until it can easily be removed with a push of the finger as you draw the pistol. It also has space on the belt to hold a dozen .38 Special bullets.
The belt is a Bianchi 42 with adjustable sizing and quick connection prongs.
This is a really cool police package that will easily take you back in time to when this officer carried his gun with this belt and holster.Contact me for additional pictures.
